editorialDecl.p: EEBO-TCP is a partnership between the Universities of Michigan and Oxford and the publisher ProQuest to create accurately transcribed and encoded texts based on the image sets published by ProQuest via their Early English Books Online (EEBO) database (http://eebo.chadwyck.com). The general aim of EEBO-TCP is to encode one copy (usually the first edition) of every monographic English-language title published between 1473 and 1700 available in EEBO.

EEBO-TCP aimed to produce large quantities of textual data within the usual project restraints of time and funding, and therefore chose to create diplomatic transcriptions (as opposed to critical editions) with light-touch, mainly structural encoding based on the Text Encoding Initiative (http://www.tei-c.org).

The EEBO-TCP project was divided into two phases. The 25,368 texts created during Phase 1 of the project (2000-2009), initially available only to institutions that contributed to their creation, were released into the public domain on 1 January 2015. The approximately 40,000 texts produced during Phase 2 (2009- ), of which 34,963 had been released as of 2020, originally similarly restricted, were similarly freed from all restrictions on 1 August 2020. As of that date anyone is free to take and use these texts for any purpose (modify them, annotate them, distribute them, etc.). But we do respectfully request that due credit and attribution be given to their original source.
Users should be aware of the process of creating the TCP texts, and therefore of any assumptions that can be made about the data.

Text selection was based on the New Cambridge Bibliography of English Literature (NCBEL). If an author (or for an anonymous work, the title) appears in NCBEL, then their works are eligible for inclusion. Selection was intended to range over a wide variety of subject areas, to reflect the true nature of the print record of the period. In general, first editions of a works in English were prioritized, although there are a number of works in other languages, notably Latin and Welsh, included and sometimes a second or later edition of a work was chosen if there was a compelling reason to do so.

Image sets were sent to external keying companies for transcription and basic encoding. Quality assurance was then carried out by editorial teams in Oxford and Michigan. 5% (or 5 pages, whichever is the greater) of each text was proofread for accuracy and those which did not meet QA standards were returned to the keyers to be redone. After proofreading, the encoding was enhanced and/or corrected and characters marked as illegible were corrected where possible up to a limit of 100 instances per text. Any remaining illegibles were encoded as <gap>s. Understanding these processes should make clear that, while the overall quality of TCP data is very good, some errors will remain and some readable characters will be marked as illegible. Users should bear in mind that in all likelihood such instances will never have been looked at by a TCP editor.
The texts were encoded and linked to page images in accordance with level 4 of the TEI in Libraries guidelines.

Copies of the texts have been issued variously as SGML (TCP schema; ASCII text with mnemonic sdata character entities); displayable XML (TCP schema; characters represented either as UTF-8 Unicode or text strings within braces); or lossless XML (TEI P5, characters represented either as UTF-8 Unicode or TEI g elements).
Keying and markup guidelines are available at the Text Creation Partnership web site.

div.p: I Do as far as in me lyeth, Licenſe and Authoriſe the Imprinting of this Book, Intituled, A Second Book of Judgements.
To Aprilis 1674. JO. VAUGHAN.
A SECOND BOOK OF Judgements. In Real, Perſonal, and Mixt Actions, and upon the STATUTE; All or moſt of them affirmed upon Writs of Error.

BEING, The COLLECTION of George Huxley, of Lincolns-Inne Gent. out of the choice Manuſcripts of Mr. Brownlowe, and Mr. Moyle, ſometimes Prothonotaries of the COMMON-PLEAS; As alſo of Mr. Smythier, formerly Secondary of the ſame Court.
Peruſed, Tranſcribed, and ſomewhat Corrected, and Tabled, with Addition of ſome Notes, by George Towneſend Eſq Second Prothonotary of the Common Pleas.
Very Uſeful and Neceſſary for all Prothonotaries, Secondaries, Students, Clerks of JUDGEMENTS, and all ſorts of Perſons any way relating to the Law.
LONDON, Printed by T. R. and N. T. for George Dawes over againſt Lincolns-Inne-Gate in Chancery Lane, 1674.

div.head: To the READER.
div.p:
A Book of JUDGEMENTS, (out of which this was tranſcribed) coming to the hands of a Stationer, who deſired to have it Printed if it might be thought fitting; He requested my Peruſal thereof, and furtherance therein: I found the ſame to be most of Special Judgements, or Entries in the Court of Common Pleas, in the times of King JAMES, Queen ELIZABETH, and ſome Ancienter, for the moſt part ill written, with too many Abbreviations by &c. without Order, Table, or fitting Marginal Notes. Yet finding most part to be of good Matter and Forms, and thinking it fit to be Publiſhed:
I firſt Tabled it, and then cauſed it to be written forth in as good a Method as I could; which I Peruſed, and ſomewhat Corrected, adding Marginal Notes. I conceive the ſame principally to concern the Prothonotaries of the Court of Common Pleas, and their Clerks of Judgements, but may be often uſeful to Clerks of the Kings Bench, the Exchequer, Ireland, Counties Palatine, Franchiſes, and Corporarions, and many other Practicers at Law. Publick Charity more than any my own Profit, concerns, or Interest, incited me to this work, which, if well accepted, I have my ends. I ſtile this A Second Book of Judgements, there being a former Book of Judgements in Engliſh, Publiſhed in the Year, 1655.

div.p:
(1) Judicium ſuper inſufficien' placito in Abatement q'd quer' recuperet debitum & dampna. ſſ. PAſchae 41 Eliz. Rot. 2504. Videtur eiſdem Iuſtic hic qd pdcm plitum pdci defend ſuꝑius in caſſaconem bris & narr pdco

div.head: Actio ſuper Statut'.
div.p:
(1) Def. in actione de hutes' & clam' cogn' actionem. ſſ. HIll. 1 Jac. Rot. 2269. Et pdci hōies inh̄itan ꝑ T. D. Attorn ſuu ven & defend vim & injur quando &c. Et dic qd ipi non poſſunt dedice acconem pdci W. pocam nec quin ipi ſunt culpabiles de pmiſſis ſuꝑius eis impōit contra formam Statuti pdci modo & forma ꝓut pdcus W. qui tam &c. ſuꝑius vſus eos queritur & qd pdcus W. qui tam &c. dampna ſua occone pmiſſa vſus pfat hōies h̄itan recuꝑare debeat Set quia neſcitur que dampna pdcus W. ſuſtinuit occone pmiſſa prec eſt Vic qd ꝑ ſacrm ꝓbo
rum & legliu homin be ballia ſua diligent inquir que dampna pdcus W. qui tam &c. ſuſtinuit tam occone pmiſſa qm ꝓ mis & cuſtag ſuis ꝑ ipm circa ſectam ſuam in hac parte appōit. Et inquiſiconem quam &c. Vic conſtare fac hic (tli retorn) ſub ſigillo &c. & ſigillis &c. Iudgmentsr ceo.

(2) In Hutes' & clam' Iudicium pro quer' ſuper general' veredictum pro parte ubi ſuit ſpecialc veredictum pro alia parte. ſſ. PAſchae 9 Jac. Rot. 1115. Ad quem diem &c. Poſtea &c. Et ſuꝑ hoc idem T. pet Iudm vſus pfat hōies inh̄itantes in hundrō de C. pdca ſuꝑ genali vedcō
pdcō unde Iura pdca ꝓ eodem T. vſus eoſdem hōies in h̄itantes tranſivit ſibi reddi Suꝑ quo viſis pmiſſis & ꝑ Iuſtic hic plenius intellcis cons eſt qd pdcus T. qui tam &c. recuꝑet vſus pfat hōies inh̄itances dampna ſua pdca ad &c. necnon &c. que quidem dampna &c. inde in mia &c.

(3) Judicium in hutes' & clam' pro quer' ſuper ſpecial' veredicto de validitate ſacr'i. ſſ. PAſchae 43 El. Rot. 953. Iudm ſuꝑ ſpiali vedcō in Hutes & clam, qd pdcm ſacrm ꝑ pfat R. coram pfat R. L. in forma pdca fcm eſt bonu & validum in lege juxta formam Statuti pdci. Et qd pdcihōies in h̄itantes ſuntcu lpabiles &c.

(4) Non pros' in Hutes' & clam'. ſſ. HIll. 16 Jac. Rot. 729. Plt en hue & crie non ꝓs ad Aſſias Iō
&c. ut in al. Et qd pdci in h̄itantes eant inde ſine die &c. 73 l. ꝓ mis &c.

(5) Judicium pro quer' ſuperveredicto ſuper Statut' de proſecutione in Cur' Admiralitatis. ſſ. MIch. 31 H. 6. Rot. 315. M. 22 H. 6. Rot. 327. Nar ſuꝑ Statut de Anno 13 R. 2. & Anno 2 H. 6. vſus eos qui ꝓſequuntur aliquas querelas in Cur Admiralitatis ꝓ contract fact in Corpore Com ubi defi dic qd non ꝓs fuit & Iſſue de ceo. Et al Niſi prius Iur dic ſuꝑ ſacrm ſuu qd pdcus defi plitm infra-ſpec ꝓſequur fuit ꝓut pdcus quer ꝓ b̄re & narr ſua pdca vſus eum queritur Et aſſid da ipius quer occone tranſgr & contempt infra ſpec ult mis &c. ad Centum Marcas et ꝓ mis &c. ad 11 s. Iō cons eſt qd pdcus quer recuꝑet vſus pfat defi dampna ſua in duplo que quidem dampna in duplo ſe attiugunt ad 200 mcas Et qd Dominus Rex recuꝑet vſus pfat defi penam 10 l. ꝓ ꝓſecucone ſua contra formam Statuti pdci ſic fact. Et pdcus defi capiatur &c.

(6) Indicium pro quer' ſuper Statut' de malefactoribus in parcis. ſſ. CApiantur &c. Et h̄eant priſonam triu Anno
rum & ptea redimantur ad voluntat Dne Regine ſi h̄eant • nde redimi poſſunt. Et nihilominus inveniant bonam ſecuritatem qd amplius non malefac. Et ſi poſt impriſonament triu anno
rum non h̄eant unde redimi poſſunt inveniant eandem ſecuritatem & ſi ſecuritatem humoi invenire non poſſunt regnu abjurent &c.

(7) Alit'. ſſ. CApiantur &c. ad finem cum Dnō Rege faciend. Et h̄eant priſonam triu anno
rum . Et inveniant bonam ſecuritatem qd amplius non malefac Et ſi poſt impriſonamentum triu anno
